{
  "texts": [
    "Furthermore, most datasets were unaccompanied by a licence before 2022 (~50-80%), compared to only 12% in 2023.",
    "The shift to more licence use, and to more restrictive licences, may foreshadow future challenges to open data.",
    "80 Requires attribution Requires share-alike Allowed use: commercial Allowed use: non-commercial/academic Allowed use: custom (15.7%) 87 (12.3%) 68 Counts (11.6%) 64 (10.7%) 59 (9.6%) 53 (6.0%) 33 (5.4%) 30 (3.4%) 19 (3.3%) 18 (3.1%) 17 (2.9%) 16 (2.5%) 14 (2.5%) 14 (2.0%) 11 (1.8%) 10 (1.3%) 7 (0.9%) 5 (0.7%) 4 (0.7%) 4 (0.4%) 2 (0.4%) 2 We find a long tail of custom licences, adopted from software for data: 73% of all licences require attribution and 33% share-alike, but the most popular are usually commercially permissive.",
    "https://doi.org/10.1038/s42256-024-00878-8",
    "Commercial datasets have greater language variety, but low-resource language datasets see the least commercial coverage."
  ]
